            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>Take Duke&rsquo;s comfortable win over Clemson Jan. 3. After the Blue Devils raced out to a 30-12 halftime advantage on the strength of a solid defensive effort, the Tigers went on an 11-0 run to start the second half. The Blue Devils shots during that run were all contested 3-pointers, and all were missed. Head coach Mike Krzyzewski called time out, and Duke came out of the break noticeably more aggressive&mdash;the guards were feeding the ball to post players or driving to the basket themselves. &nbsp;</p>
<p>The Blue Devils renewed interest in feeding the post&mdash;and especially the added wrinkle of feeding Mason Plumlee or Lance Thomas at the high post&mdash;gives this year&rsquo;s team another way to get the ball into the paint. And&mdash;wouldn&rsquo;t you know it?&mdash;Duke&rsquo;s shots are falling more frequently this year than last; its eFG% is 53.8% versus last year&rsquo;s 50.5%.</p>
<p>So next time you&rsquo;re watching the Blue Devils and &ldquo;the shots just aren&rsquo;t falling,&rdquo; think a little harder. Why aren&rsquo;t they falling? Is Duke attacking on offense? And if you ask these questions and you answer them the same way I do, then you&rsquo;ll probably also agree with this: Duke is capable of beating any team in the country&mdash;as long as it plays attacking, aggressive offensive basketball. And given the right coaching, the right mindset, the right matchups and the right luck, it&rsquo;s almost easy to envision a team doing that for six straight games.</p>

